Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{0.5%tsp}.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine the @breadcrumbs{50%g}, @hard Italian style cheese{40%g}(grated) and the @olive oil{2%tbsp} for the crumb. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and set aside.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}.

Slice the @potatoes{450%g} into 1cm thick rounds (no need to peel).

Once boiling, add the potato slices to the water and simmer until you can easily slip a knife through, ~{8-12%minutes}. Drain in a #colander{}.

== Chickpea Masala ==

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{240%g} to the pan. Cook until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn occasionally. Once browned, add the @korma curry paste{50%g}, @North Indian style spice mix{1%sachet} and garlic. Stir-fry for ~{30%seconds}.

Stir in the @water{75%ml} for the sauce, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and chickpeas.

Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until the liquid has slightly reduced, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Once the sauce is reduced slightly, stir in the @mango chutney{40%g} and @creme fraiche{150%g}. Mix well to combine.

Add the @baby spinach{100%g} to the pan a handful at a time until it's wilted and piping hot and the chicken is cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed, then remove from the heat.

Meanwhile, preheat your #grill{} to high.

Once the potatoes are ready, transfer the chickpea mixture to an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}.

Lay the potato slices evenly on top of the chickpeas, then sprinkle over the cheesy crumb.

Pop under the grill until golden on top, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Once the chicken masala pie is ready, share it out between your serving plates and tuck in.

Enjoy!